          <div class="article-intro">
            <p class="lead">If you're considering short-term rentals in Toronto, understanding the city's night limits is essential. Toronto enforces strict regulations on Airbnb and other short-term rental platforms, with the most important rule being the <strong>180-night annual limit</strong> for entire home rentals.</p>
          </div>

          <h2 id="what-is-limit">What is the 180-Night Limit?</h2>
          <p>Toronto's short-term rental bylaw restricts <strong>entire home rentals</strong> to a maximum of 180 nights per calendar year. This means if you rent out your complete property (when you're not there), you can only do so for roughly half the year.</p>

          <div class="callout">
            <div class="callout-icon">
              <svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
                <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"></circle>
                <path d="M12 16v-4"></path>
                <path d="M12 8h.01"></path>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="callout-content">
              <strong>Key Point:</strong> Partial unit rentals (renting a room while you stay in the property) have <strong>no night limit</strong>. This is an important distinction many hosts overlook.
            </div>
          </div>

          <h2 id="who-does-it-apply">Who Does the Limit Apply To?</h2>
          <p>The 180-night limit applies to any property registered as a short-term rental in Toronto where:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>The property is your <strong>principal residence</strong></li>
            <li>You're renting the <strong>entire unit</strong> (not just a room)</li>
            <li>Rentals are for <strong>less than 28 consecutive days</strong></li>
          </ul>

          <p>The principal residence requirement is crucial. In Toronto, you can only operate a short-term rental from the home where you actually live. Investment properties and secondary homes are not eligible for short-term rentals under 28 days.</p>

          <h2 id="how-nights-counted">How Are Nights Counted?</h2>
          <p>Toronto counts nights on a calendar year basis (January 1 to December 31). Here's what you need to know:</p>

          <div class="info-grid">
            <div class="info-card">
              <h4>Entire Home Rentals</h4>
              <p>Each night your entire property is booked counts toward your 180-night limit.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card">
              <h4>Partial Unit Rentals</h4>
              <p>Nights when you rent a room while home don't count toward the limit.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card">
              <h4>Multiple Platforms</h4>
              <p>Nights across all platforms (Airbnb, VRBO, etc.) are combined in the count.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <h2 id="registration">Registration Requirements</h2>
          <p>Before you can legally operate a short-term rental in Toronto, you must:</p>

          <ol>
            <li><strong>Register with the City</strong> - Apply through Toronto's Municipal Licensing & Standards</li>
            <li><strong>Obtain a registration number</strong> - This must be displayed on all listings</li>
            <li><strong>Prove principal residence</strong> - Provide documentation showing it's your primary home</li>
            <li><strong>Maintain compliance</strong> - Keep records and renew registration as required</li>
          </ol>

          <p>Registration costs approximately $50 and must be renewed annually. Operating without valid registration can result in significant fines.</p>

          <h2 id="mat-tax">The 8.5% MAT Tax</h2>
          <p>Toronto charges a <strong>Municipal Accommodation Tax (MAT)</strong> of 8.5% on all short-term rentals. This tax is:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Collected automatically by Airbnb and remitted to the city</li>
            <li>Applied to the accommodation portion of your booking</li>
            <li>One of the highest MAT rates in Ontario</li>
          </ul>

          <p>As a host, you don't need to manually collect or remit this tax when using major platforms, but you should understand it affects your guests' total cost.</p>

          <h2 id="penalties">Penalties for Non-Compliance</h2>
          <p>Toronto actively enforces its short-term rental rules. Penalties include:</p>

          <div class="warning-box">
            <h4>Potential Fines:</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Up to <strong>$10,000</strong> for individuals per offense</li>
              <li>Up to <strong>$50,000</strong> for corporations per offense</li>
              <li>Registration revocation</li>
              <li>Platform account suspension</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <p>The city uses data from platforms and neighbour complaints to identify non-compliant listings. Enforcement has increased significantly since the bylaws were introduced.</p>

          <h2 id="compliance-tips">Tips for Staying Compliant</h2>
          <p>To avoid issues with Toronto's STR regulations:</p>

          <ul class="tips-list">
            <li><span class="tip-icon">1</span> <strong>Track your nights carefully</strong> - Use a spreadsheet or property management software to monitor your entire-home rental nights.</li>
            <li><span class="tip-icon">2</span> <strong>Consider mid-term rentals</strong> - Rentals of 28+ days are exempt from STR regulations and the night limit.</li>
            <li><span class="tip-icon">3</span> <strong>Keep documentation</strong> - Maintain records of all bookings, registration, and principal residence proof.</li>
            <li><span class="tip-icon">4</span> <strong>Display your registration</strong> - Always show your valid registration number on all listing platforms.</li>
            <li><span class="tip-icon">5</span> <strong>Work with professionals</strong> - A property management company can help ensure compliance while maximizing your returns.</li>
          </ul>

